article.description: Drew Neitzel scored 32 points and Isaiah Dahlman added 11, both career highs, for sluggish Michigan State in a 69-61 escape against Chicago State on Saturday night.
article.headline: Sluggish Spartans squeak past Chicago State
article.linkText: Sluggish Spartans squeak past Chicago State
article.story: EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Drew Neitzel scored 32 points and Isaiah Dahlman added 11, both career highs, for sluggish Michigan State (No. 23 ESPN/USA Today; unranked AP) in a 69-61 escape against Chicago State on Saturday night. Neitzel had six 3-point baskets and Dahlman connected on drives and free throws in his first start for the step-slow Spartans (10-2), who survived despite 21 turnovers. Royce Parran scored 20 points, David Holston had 18 and Kourtney Calvin 12 for the Cougars (4-9), who nearly pulled a major upset in their eighth of 12 straight games away from home. An alley-oop slam by the 5-foot-8 Parran put Chicago State ahead 44-43 with just over nine minutes left. But Neitzel quickly answered with a short jumper, a 3 from the wing and assists on Goran Suton's first two baskets for an eight-point lead. Leading 31-23, Michigan State coach Tom Izzo started walk-ons Brandon Darnton and DeMarcus Ducre at guard in the second half to send a message to his team. Instead, the Cougars responded and would have led 33-32 if they had made two free throws with 16:07 left. A technical foul on Chicago State coach Kevin Jones helped the Spartans hit four straight free throws with 14:42 to play. And two missed dunks kept the Cougars from turning a scare into a Michigan State deficit. They trailed just 65-61 with 40 seconds left. Jones said he was physically challenged by guard Cam-Ron Clay at halftime and wouldn't have him back on the team. Jones wanted Chicago State officials to find alternate transportation home for Clay, whom he said should join the military if he wanted to fight.
